│ stop({"edit_points": [[413, 434,                                         │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/CorrelatedValuePropagation.cpp"]],           │
│ "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe pass Correlated Value      │
│ Propagation (CVP) is transforming a switch in a loop in a way that       │
│ renders valid source behavior (reaching exit) into UB by making the      │
│ default destination unreachable. Alive2 reports the transformation as    │
│ incorrect: the source can reach %exit via the initial -1 (255) value     │
│ flowing into the switch, while the target unconditionally goes to an     │
│ unreachable block. This indicates CVP incorrectly concluded the default  │
│ case is unreachable.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe opt output shows    │
│ the first transformation occurs in processSwitch(), which removes cases  │
│ and then, based on a ConstantRange query, may create a new unreachable   │
│ default block. The backtrace confirms the first mutation happens via     │
│ BasicBlock::removePredecessor called from processSwitch(). The pass then │
│ ConstantFoldTerminator() and ends up with a CFG where %exit has no       │
│ predecessors and a new default.unreachable is introduced.\n\n3. Root     │
│ Cause Analysis:\nThe problematic logic is in processSwitch() when        │
│ deciding to mark the default destination as unreachable:\n\n  - The code │
│ computes a ConstantRange CR for the switch condition at its use and then │
│ checks if !CR.isSizeLargerThan(ReachableCaseCount). If true, it assumes  │
│ that all possible values of the condition are covered by the set of      │
│ remaining cases, and thus it replaces the default with an unreachable    │
│ block.\n\n  - This heuristic is unsound. ReachableCaseCount counts       │
│ distinct case labels remaining, but CR represents a range of possible    │
│ values, which may include values not equal to any of the remaining case  │
│ constants. A non-strict size comparison cannot guarantee that the set of │
│ possible values exactly equals the set of case constants. In loops with  │
│ self-edges and PHIs (as in the reproducer), LVI may infer a narrow CR at │
│ the use in the loop header/backedge (e.g., only values seen on the       │
│ backedge), while values from other incoming edges (like the entry) are   │
│ still possible during actual execution. As a result, CVP may conclude    │
│ the default is unreachable when it is actually reachable from another    │
│ predecessor.\n\n  - The code also mutates the CFG (removing case edges)  │
│ before performing the default-unreachable decision, which can trigger    │
│ local PHI simplifications and change the switch condition                │
│ (SI->getCondition()). This combined with relying on CR size makes the    │
│ decision more fragile and leads to the misoptimization observed.\n\n4.   │
│ Proposed Edit Point(s):\nModify processSwitch() to use a sound criterion │
│ for marking the default as unreachable. Instead of relying on            │
│ ConstantRange size vs. case count, perform a per-predecessor LVI check   │
│ to prove that, on every incoming edge, the condition equals one of the   │
│ remaining case constants. Only if this is proven for all predecessors,   │
│ consider the default unreachable. Otherwise, leave the default           │
│ as-is.\n\nEdit location:                                                 │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/CorrelatedValuePropagation.cpp lines          │
│ 413-434.\n\nReplacement sketch (conceptual):\n- Remove the ConstantRange │
│ size check and subsequent default.unreachable creation.\n- Implement a   │
│ loop over predecessors of BB. For each predecessor Pred, query LVI for   │
│ Cond==Case for each remaining case. If for some Pred, none of the cases  │
