  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe pass Correlated Value
Propagation (CVP) is transforming a switch in a loop in a way that renders
valid source behavior (reaching exit) into UB by making the default
destination unreachable. Alive2 reports the transformation as incorrect: the
source can reach %exit via the initial -1 (255) value flowing into the
switch, while the target unconditionally goes to an unreachable block. This
indicates CVP incorrectly concluded the default case is unreachable.\n\n2.
Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe opt output shows the first transformation occurs
in processSwitch(), which removes cases and then, based on a ConstantRange
query, may create a new unreachable default block. The backtrace confirms
the first mutation happens via BasicBlock::removePredecessor called from
processSwitch(). The pass then ConstantFoldTerminator() and ends up with a
CFG where %exit has no predecessors and a new default.unreachable is
introduced.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe problematic logic is in
processSwitch() when deciding to mark the default destination as
unreachable:\n\n  - The code computes a ConstantRange CR for the switch
condition at its use and then checks if
!CR.isSizeLargerThan(ReachableCaseCount). If true, it assumes that all
possible values of the condition are covered by the set of remaining cases,
and thus it replaces the default with an unreachable block.\n\n  - This
heuristic is unsound. ReachableCaseCount counts distinct case labels
remaining, but CR represents a range of possible values, which may include
values not equal to any of the remaining case constants. A non-strict size
comparison cannot guarantee that the set of possible values exactly equals
the set of case constants. In loops with self-edges and PHIs (as in the
reproducer), LVI may infer a narrow CR at the use in the loop
header/backedge (e.g., only values seen on the backedge), while values from
other incoming edges (like the entry) are still possible during actual
execution. As a result, CVP may conclude the default is unreachable when it
is actually reachable from another predecessor.\n\n  - The code also mutates
the CFG (removing case edges) before performing the default-unreachable
decision, which can trigger local PHI simplifications and change the switch
condition (SI->getCondition()). This combined with relying on CR size makes
the decision more fragile and leads to the misoptimization observed.\n\n4.
Proposed Edit Point(s):\nModify processSwitch() to use a sound criterion for
marking the default as unreachable. Instead of relying on ConstantRange size
vs. case count, perform a per-predecessor LVI check to prove that, on every
incoming edge, the condition equals one of the remaining case constants.
Only if this is proven for all predecessors, consider the default
unreachable. Otherwise, leave the default as-is.\n\nEdit location:
llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/CorrelatedValuePropagation.cpp lines
413-434.\n\nReplacement sketch (conceptual):\n- Remove the ConstantRange
size check and subsequent default.unreachable creation.\n- Implement a loop
over predecessors of BB. For each predecessor Pred, query LVI for Cond==Case
for each remaining case. If for some Pred, none of the cases can be proven
to fire (all Res are zero or unknown), then do not mark default unreachable.
If for all Pred, at least one case can be proven to fire, then default is
unreachable, and perform the transformation to create
default.unreachable.\n- Keep DTU updates as before when we do
transform.\n\nThis change avoids the unsound assumption and ensures that the
default is only removed when LVI proves the switch must go to some case on
all edges.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe bug stems from using
ConstantRange::isSizeLargerThan(ReachableCaseCount) as a proxy for \"all
cases are covered\", which is not sound. By replacing it with an explicit
per-predecessor proof using LVI that guarantees some case fires for each
incoming edge, we prevent removing a reachable default. This fixes the
misoptimization in the reproducer and maintains correctness while still
enabling valid simplifications.",
